Abstract: Clinton administration officials said today that President Boris N. Yeltsin's surprise resignation would not dramatically alter relations with Russia and could improve the chances that Moscow and Washington will break a stalemate over a major arms control treaty.     By advancing Russia's presidential elections by three months, to late March, Mr. Yeltsin's decision might allow the newly elected Russian leader to negotiate with authority Washington's proposal to modify the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, administration officials said.
